      <item>
        <title>Cash flow at risk (CFAR)</title>
        <description>&lt;p&gt;Companies that are part of the “real” economy can barely assess their risk of
business activities with the &lt;a href=&quot;var.html&quot;&gt;VAR&lt;/a&gt; approach. They would rather want to know the
shortfall of their expected cash flows.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;script type=&quot;math/tex; mode=display&quot;&gt;CVAR = \alpha  \sigma_{CF}&lt;/script&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Example: we expect cash flows of $10m over the next year, their volatility is
$3m.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;script type=&quot;math/tex; mode=display&quot;&gt;CVAR_{5%} = 1.65 * $3m = $4.95m&lt;/script&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thus, there is a 5% chance that cash flows fall below $5.05m (10-4.95) in the
next year.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Assumptions:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;cash flows are normally distributed&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;we know their volatility&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;this volatility is constant for the period in question&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
</description>
